===Noun===
{{en-noun|~|abiogeneses}}

# {{lb|en|evolutionary theory}} The [[origination]] of [[living]] [[organism]]s from [[lifeless]] matter; such [[genesis]] as does not [[involve]] the action of living [[parent#Noun|parents]]. {{defdate|from 1870}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=[Thomas Henry Huxley]|authorlink=Thomas Huxley|title=The President’s Address|magazine=[[w:The Athenaeum (British magazine)|The Athenæum: Journal of English and Foreign Literature, Science, the Fine Arts, Music and the Drama]]|location=London|publisher=Printed by Edward J. Francis, Took's Court, {{w|Chancery Lane}}, published at the office, 20, Wellington Street, [[w:Strand, London|Strand]], W.C., by John Francis. [...]|date=17 September 1870|issue=2238|page=374|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dk9DAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA374|columns=2–3|oclc=956082422|passage=And thus the hypothesis that living matter always arises by the agency of pre-existing living matter, took definite shape; {{...}} It will be necessary for me to refer to this hypothesis so frequently, that, to save circumlocution, I shall call it the hypothesis of ''Biogenesis''; and I shall term the contrary doctrine—that living matter may be produced by not living matter—the hypothesis of '''''Abiogenesis'''''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Societies and Academies: Philadelphia|journal=[[w:Nature (journal)|Nature: A Weekly Illustrated Journal of Science]]|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan and Co.]]|date=3 October 1872|volume=VI|page=472|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=bJ5FAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA467|column=2|oclc=64051812|passage=The assertion of [[w:Louis Pasteur|[Louis] Pasteur]] is justified, that the ''onus probandi'' [burden of proof] lies with abiogenesists, since there is no experience of any living form more than {{frac|1|1000}} of an inch in diameter springing to life out of inorganic matter; it is therefore vastly improbable (needing most cogent evidence to prove), that any form less than {{frac|1|1000}} of an inch in size can be made to spring into life from inorganic matter. While '''abiogenesis''' is unproved, we hold to the conclusion that vital force is not the mere outcome or resultant of any or all of the other cosmic forces.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Cyril C. Means, Jr.|journal=[[w:Congressional Record|Congressional Record: Proceedings and Debates [...]]]|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher=[[w:United States Government Publishing Office|U.S. Government Printing Office]]|year=1971|volume=117, part 23|page=30820|column=3|oclc=608021596|passage=Life ''began''. There was one '''abiogenesis''' when something happened to turn inanimate matter into animate cells. And it happened only once. There are no '''abiogeneses''' today. Human life is continuous. Human persons are discontinuous and individual.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Eric Voegelin|authorlink=Eric Voegelin|author2=Ruth Hein, transl.|chapter=Race as Biological Unit|editor={{w|Klaus Vondung}}|title=Race and State: Translated from the German|series=The Collected Works of Eric Voegelin|seriesvolume=2|location=Baton Rouge, La.; London|publisher={{w|Louisiana State University Press}}|year=1997|section=part I (The Systematic Content of Race Theory)|page=45|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=y5nhoISw64YC&pg=PA45|isbn=978-0-8071-1842-9|passage=According to [[w:Carl Nägeli|[Carl] Nägeli]], the highest forms have evolved from the oldest cells produced through '''abiogenesis''', and the lower forms are, depending on their position in the hierarchy, the descendants of respectively more recent '''abiogenesis'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=G. Bradley Schaefer|author2=James N. Thompson, Jr.|chapter=Genetics: Unity and Diversity|title=Medical Genetics: An Integrated Approach|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|McGraw-Hill Education}}|year=2014|page=3|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=6ZXbAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA3|isbn=978-0-07-166438-7|passage=Although '''abiogenesis''', the spontaneous creation of a living system under appropriate conditions, must have occurred at the end of the prebiotic world, spontaneous generation of life no longer occurs.}}

